04131nam a22006255i 9781575066301DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750663017 a10.1515/97815750663012doi  a(DE-B1597)584215  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a220.60921 aHolsinger-Friesen, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIrenaeus and Genesis :bA Study of Competition in Early Christian Hermeneutics /cThomas Holsinger-Friesen. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (266 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJournal of Theological Interpretation Supplements ;v100tFrontmatter -- tTABLE OF CONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tABBREVIATIONS -- t1. GENESIS: RECAPITULATION AND PROTOLOGICAL PERSPECTIVE -- t2. COMPETITION: GNOSTIC INTERPRETATIONS OF GENESIS -- t3. GENESIS 1.26 AND THE DIVINE ECONOMY -- t4. GENESIS 2.7 AND THE HOMO VIVENS -- tCONCLUSION -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tAUTHOR INDEX -- tSCRIPTURE INDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIrenaeus, the second-century bishop of Lyons, left such an impression upon the church that he is sometimes considered to be theology's "founding father." After all, his legacy includes such theological landmarks as the regula fidei (or "rule of faith") and the doctrine of recapitulation. Although these ought not to be minimized, we may gain a new appreciation for this early bishop by highlighting a facet of his work that is even more central: the distinctive shape of the hermeneutic guiding his readings of sacred texts as Christian Scripture. Within the contemporary climate of twenty-first century theology, the reopening of questions of power, truth, authenticity, and holism points to a critique of hermeneutical process (not just theological end-product). In Irenaeus's day, Gnostic Christians on the fringe of the church offered a vision of the telos of faith that many found compelling. Responding to this challenge required Irenaeus to articulate an even more satisfying Christian theology and anthropology on the basis of Scripture and received apostolic tradition. In this battle of hermeneutics, both sides considered protological texts such as Genesis 1:26 and 2:7 to be indispensible. Through a sympathetic reading, then, of Irenaeus and his competitors, we aim to better understand why Irenaeus's biblical interpretations ultimately were deemed more plausible, faithful, and fruitful within the mainstream of the church.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781575066301zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781575066301423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781575066301.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK